 {"id":"rust_proxy-giu","title":"Feature: Systemd service file generation","description":"## Overview

Add a command to generate systemd service files for easy deployment on Linux servers with proper security hardening.

## Strategic Value (Score: 8/10)

Systemd is the standard init system on modern Linux. Providing a ready-to-use service file:
- Dramatically simplifies server deployment
- Ensures proper startup/shutdown behavior
- Enables systemctl integration (start/stop/restart/status)
- Applies security best practices automatically
- Makes the tool feel production-ready

## Background and Rationale

### Current State
Users who want to run the proxy as a system service must manually:
1. Write a systemd unit file
2. Figure out correct paths and options
3. Apply security hardening (capabilities, sandboxing)
4. Handle reload via ExecReload

### The Solution
One command generates a complete, secure service file:

```bash
$ rp service generate
Generated systemd service file: /tmp/rp.service

To install:
  sudo cp /tmp/rp.service /etc/systemd/system/
  sudo systemctl daemon-reload
  sudo systemctl enable --now rp
```

## Service File Features

### Basic Configuration
```ini
[Unit]
Description=Rust Proxy - High-performance HTTPS proxy
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=notify
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/rp start --foreground
ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=5
```

### Security Hardening
```ini
# Sandboxing
ProtectSystem=strict
ProtectHome=true
PrivateTmp=true
NoNewPrivileges=true

# Capabilities (only what's needed)
CapabilityBoundingSet=CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
AmbientCapabilities=CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE

# Resource limits
LimitNOFILE=65535
```

### Logging Integration
```ini
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal
SyslogIdentifier=rp
```

## Implementation Plan

The feature is broken into these subtasks:
1. Add service generate command to CLI
2. Implement service file template with placeholders
3. Add security hardening options
4. Add install helper command

## Configuration Options

```bash
$ rp service generate --help
Generate systemd service file

Options:
  --output <path>      Output path (default: /tmp/rp.service)
  --user <user>        Run as user (default: root)
  --group <group>      Run as group (default: root)
  --config <path>      Config file path
  --hardened           Apply maximum security hardening
  --install            Also install to /etc/systemd/system/
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- `rp service generate` creates valid systemd unit
- Security hardening applied by default
- Config path customizable
- User/group configurable
- Optional direct installation
